ADR-001: Company is the Aggregate Root

This was probably our first major decision.

We agreed that:

All external operations begin with Company.
Company coordinates cross-entity business rules.
Employee and Department own their own state.

This decision has influenced:

hire_employee()
transfer_employee()
change_salary()
and our proposed assign_manager().
ADR-002: Encapsulation of Entity State

Remember when we changed:

employees

to:

_employees

and exposed:

@property
def employees(self) -> tuple[Employee, ...]:

That wasn't just a refactor.

It was an architectural decision:

Internal collections remain mutable.

External consumers receive read-only views.

That protects our aggregate.

ADR-003: Persistence Separation

This came from our persistence deep dive.

We agreed that:

Company

knows nothing about:

JSON
files
storage

while:

JsonStorage

knows nothing about:

Employees
Departments
business rules

The repository is the bridge.

That was another architectural decision.

ADR-004: Reconstruction Mirrors Persistence

One of my favourite discussions.

We concluded:

Save

Company
↓

to_dict()
↓

dictionary
↓

JSON

is mirrored by:

JSON
↓

dictionary
↓

from_dict()
↓

Company

We also agreed each class reconstructs itself:

Employee.from_dict()

Department.from_dict()

Company.from_dict()

rather than Company rebuilding every object manually.

ADR-005: Entity Owns State Changes

This emerged naturally.

Instead of:

employee.salary = ...

we agreed on:

employee.change_salary(...)

Later it became:

employee.deactivate()

employee.assign_manager(...)

The principle became:

The object that owns the state owns the mutation.

ADR-006: Preserve Business Events

This is the one we discovered today.

Instead of:

Leave Balance = 12

we record:

+22 Entitlement

-5 Annual Leave

+1 Adjustment

and derive the balance.

This is a brand-new architectural decision.